    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Is a Graph-Based Agent?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A graph-based agent is an agentic system whose control flow is expressed as a directed graph. Each node in the graph is a Python function that reads from a shared state object and returns a partial update. Edges connect nodes; conditional edges let the graph branch or loop based on state values. LangGraph is the primary library for building graph-based agents in Python."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This model is explicit: every possible transition is declared at build time, which makes the system debuggable, testable, and extensible without touching existing node logic. Compare this to a chain, where control flow is embedded inside function calls and harder to inspect or modify independently."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Graph-based agent: directed node graph sharing a TypedDict state"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Core Concepts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three primitives define every LangGraph application:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "State — a TypedDict that is passed to every node. Nodes return a dict of keys to update; LangGraph merges it into the current state."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Nodes — plain Python functions (sync or async) that take state and return a partial state update. They can call LLMs, tools, databases, or any Python code."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Edges — connections between nodes. A normal edge always fires; a conditional edge calls a routing function and uses the return value to select the next node."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from typing import TypedDict\nfrom langgraph.graph import StateGraph, END\n\n# 1. Define the shared state\nclass AgentState(TypedDict):\n    query: str\n    analysis: str\n    response: str\n\n# 2. Define node functions\ndef analyse(state: AgentState) -> dict:\n    # Read from state, return partial update\n    result = some_llm.invoke(state[\"query\"])\n    return {\"analysis\": result.content}\n\ndef respond(state: AgentState) -> dict:\n    reply = formatter_llm.invoke(state[\"analysis\"])\n    return {\"response\": reply.content}\n\n# 3. Build the graph\nbuilder = StateGraph(AgentState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"analyse\", analyse)\nbuilder.add_node(\"respond\", respond)\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"analyse\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"analyse\", \"respond\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"respond\", END)\n\ngraph = builder.compile()\n\n# 4. Run it\nresult = graph.invoke({\"query\": \"Explain backpressure in streaming systems.\", \"analysis\": \"\", \"response\": \"\"})\nprint(result[\"response\"])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Conditional Edges and Branching"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A conditional edge calls a routing function after a node completes. The routing function inspects the state and returns a string key; LangGraph uses that key to look up the next node in the edge map."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from typing import Literal\n\ndef classify_query(state: AgentState) -> dict:\n    label = classify_llm.invoke(state[\"query\"]).content.strip()\n    return {\"query_type\": label}   # e.g. \"technical\", \"billing\", \"general\"\n\ndef route(state: AgentState) -> Literal[\"technical\", \"billing\", \"general\"]:\n    return state.get(\"query_type\", \"general\")\n\nbuilder.add_node(\"classify\", classify_query)\nbuilder.add_node(\"technical\", technical_handler)\nbuilder.add_node(\"billing\", billing_handler)\nbuilder.add_node(\"general\", general_handler)\n\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"classify\")\nbuilder.add_conditional_edges(\"classify\", route, {\n    \"technical\": \"technical\",\n    \"billing\":   \"billing\",\n    \"general\":   \"general\",\n})\nbuilder.add_edge(\"technical\", END)\nbuilder.add_edge(\"billing\",   END)\nbuilder.add_edge(\"general\",   END)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Loops with Conditional Edges"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Graphs can loop: a conditional edge from node B can point back to node A. The standard pattern is a refinement loop — run a step, evaluate the result, either continue or terminate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from typing import TypedDict, Annotated\nimport operator\n\nclass RefinementState(TypedDict):\n    task: str\n    draft: str\n    feedback: str\n    iterations: int\n\ndef draft(state: RefinementState) -> dict:\n    d = writer_llm.invoke(state[\"task\"] + \"\\n\\nPrevious draft:\\n\" + state.get(\"draft\",\"\"))\n    return {\"draft\": d.content, \"iterations\": state[\"iterations\"] + 1}\n\ndef review(state: RefinementState) -> dict:\n    fb = critic_llm.invoke(state[\"draft\"])\n    return {\"feedback\": fb.content}\n\ndef should_continue(state: RefinementState) -> Literal[\"draft\", \"END\"]:\n    if state[\"iterations\"] >= 3:\n        return \"END\"\n    if \"LGTM\" in state[\"feedback\"]:\n        return \"END\"\n    return \"draft\"\n\nbuilder = StateGraph(RefinementState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"draft\", draft)\nbuilder.add_node(\"review\", review)\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"draft\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"draft\", \"review\")\nbuilder.add_conditional_edges(\"review\", should_continue, {\"draft\": \"draft\", \"END\": END})\ngraph = builder.compile()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State Reducers for List Accumulation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "By default, returning a key from a node replaces the current value. To accumulate items across iterations, annotate the field with a reducer function."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from typing import Annotated\nimport operator\n\nclass SearchState(TypedDict):\n    query: str\n    results: Annotated[list[str], operator.add]   # += semantics\n    iteration: int\n\ndef search_step(state: SearchState) -> dict:\n    new_results = search_tool.invoke(state[\"query\"])\n    # Returning a list here APPENDS rather than replaces\n    return {\"results\": new_results, \"iteration\": state[\"iteration\"] + 1}\n\n# After 3 iterations, state[\"results\"] contains all accumulated results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Use Annotated reducers whenever a node in a loop produces partial results that need to accumulate. Without the reducer, each iteration would overwrite the previous results rather than extending the list."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Compiling and Checkpointing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Calling builder.compile() validates the graph (no unreachable nodes, all edge targets exist) and returns a runnable object. Passing a checkpointer enables persistence: the graph saves state at every step so runs can be resumed after interruption."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langgraph.checkpoint.memory import MemorySaver\n\ncheckpointer = MemorySaver()\ngraph = builder.compile(checkpointer=checkpointer)\n\n# thread_id groups messages into a conversation session\nconfig = {\"configurable\": {\"thread_id\": \"session-42\"}}\n\n# First invocation\nresult = graph.invoke({\"query\": \"...\", \"analysis\": \"\", \"response\": \"\"}, config=config)\n\n# Resume later — state is restored automatically from the checkpoint\nresult2 = graph.invoke({\"query\": \"follow up question\"}, config=config)\n\n# Inspect history\nfor state_snapshot in graph.get_state_history(config):\n    print(state_snapshot.values)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subgraphs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A compiled graph can be used as a node inside another graph. This lets you compose complex pipelines from independently tested sub-graphs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Build a specialist sub-graph\nsub_builder = StateGraph(SubState)\nsub_builder.add_node(\"step1\", step1_fn)\nsub_builder.add_node(\"step2\", step2_fn)\nsub_builder.set_entry_point(\"step1\")\nsub_builder.add_edge(\"step1\", \"step2\")\nsub_builder.add_edge(\"step2\", END)\nsub_graph = sub_builder.compile()\n\n# Use the compiled sub-graph as a node in the parent graph\nparent_builder = StateGraph(ParentState)\nparent_builder.add_node(\"specialist\", sub_graph)   # compiled graph as node\nparent_builder.add_node(\"other\", other_fn)\nparent_builder.set_entry_point(\"specialist\")\nparent_builder.add_edge(\"specialist\", \"other\")\nparent_builder.add_edge(\"other\", END)\nparent_graph = parent_builder.compile()"
          }
        ]
      },
