      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing Graph Nodes in Isolation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import pytest\n\ndef test_classify_node_returns_valid_type():\n    result = classify_query({\"query\": \"My payment failed\", \"query_type\": \"\", \"response\": \"\"})\n    assert result[\"query_type\"] in {\"technical\", \"billing\", \"general\"}\n\ndef test_loop_terminates():\n    state = graph.invoke({\n        \"task\": \"Write a haiku about graphs.\",\n        \"draft\": \"\",\n        \"feedback\": \"\",\n        \"iterations\": 0,\n    })\n    assert state[\"iterations\"] <= 3\n    assert len(state[\"draft\"]) > 0\n\ndef test_reducer_accumulates():\n    s1 = {\"query\": \"q\", \"results\": [], \"iteration\": 0}\n    s2 = search_step(s1)\n    s3 = search_step({**s1, \"results\": s2[\"results\"], \"iteration\": 1})\n    # With Annotated[list, operator.add], results should grow across calls\n    assert len(s3[\"results\"]) >= len(s2[\"results\"])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Interrupts and Human-in-the-Loop"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangGraph supports interrupting graph execution at a named node. The run pauses, the current state is saved, and a human (or external system) can inspect and modify the state before the graph resumes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from langgraph.checkpoint.memory import MemorySaver\n\ncheckpointer = MemorySaver()\n# interrupt_before pauses execution just before the named node runs\ngraph = builder.compile(checkpointer=checkpointer, interrupt_before=[\"review\"])\n\nconfig = {\"configurable\": {\"thread_id\": \"review-session-1\"}}\n\n# Graph runs up to (but not including) the \"review\" node, then pauses\npartial = graph.invoke({\"draft\": \"\", \"task\": \"Write a product description.\"}, config=config)\n\n# Inspect state at the pause point\ncurrent_state = graph.get_state(config)\nprint(current_state.values[\"draft\"])\n\n# Human edits the draft\ngraph.update_state(config, {\"draft\": \"Improved draft written by human.\"})\n\n# Resume — graph picks up from the \"review\" node with the updated state\nfinal = graph.invoke(None, config=config)\nprint(final[\"response\"])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "interrupt_before and interrupt_after are the primary mechanism for human-in-the-loop validation. Use them at quality gates: before publishing content, before calling an external API with side effects, or before sending a final answer to the user."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Streaming Node Outputs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangGraph's stream() method yields events as each node completes, so callers see intermediate progress rather than waiting for the entire graph to finish."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Stream mode \"updates\" yields one dict per node completion\nfor chunk in graph.stream(\n    {\"query\": \"Summarise the quarterly report.\", \"analysis\": \"\", \"response\": \"\"},\n    stream_mode=\"updates\",\n):\n    # chunk is {node_name: partial_state_update}\n    for node_name, update in chunk.items():\n        print(f\"[{node_name}] completed:\", list(update.keys()))\n\n# Stream mode \"values\" yields the full state after each step\nfor state in graph.stream(initial_state, stream_mode=\"values\"):\n    print(\"State after step:\", state)\n\n# Stream LLM tokens from inside a node using astream_events\nasync def stream_tokens():\n    async for event in graph.astream_events(initial_state, version=\"v2\"):\n        if event[\"event\"] == \"on_chat_model_stream\":\n            print(event[\"data\"][\"chunk\"].content, end=\"\", flush=True)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Parallel Node Execution"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangGraph can run multiple nodes concurrently when there are no data dependencies between them. Fan-out and fan-in patterns are expressed with multiple edges from a single source and a reducer on the receiving node."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from typing import Annotated\nimport operator\n\nclass ParallelState(TypedDict):\n    query: str\n    sub_results: Annotated[list[str], operator.add]\n    final: str\n\ndef fetch_source_a(state: ParallelState) -> dict:\n    result = source_a_tool.invoke(state[\"query\"])\n    return {\"sub_results\": [f\"A: {result}\"]}\n\ndef fetch_source_b(state: ParallelState) -> dict:\n    result = source_b_tool.invoke(state[\"query\"])\n    return {\"sub_results\": [f\"B: {result}\"]}\n\ndef merge(state: ParallelState) -> dict:\n    combined = \"\\n\".join(state[\"sub_results\"])\n    summary = summarise_llm.invoke(combined)\n    return {\"final\": summary.content}\n\nbuilder = StateGraph(ParallelState)\nbuilder.add_node(\"fetch_a\", fetch_source_a)\nbuilder.add_node(\"fetch_b\", fetch_source_b)\nbuilder.add_node(\"merge\", merge)\n# Fan-out: START connects to both fetch nodes\nbuilder.set_entry_point(\"fetch_a\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"fetch_a\", \"merge\")\n# Add fetch_b as a parallel branch from the same entry point\n# Note: LangGraph runs nodes with no dependency simultaneously\nbuilder.add_node(\"__start___b\", fetch_source_b)  # workaround: use add_edge from START\nbuilder.add_edge(\"fetch_b\", \"merge\")\nbuilder.add_edge(\"merge\", END)"
          }
